03545nam a22004455i 9780773566002DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19961996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735660027 a10.1515/97807735660022doi  a(DE-B1597)656082  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJL27bL36 1996eb 7aPOL0400002bisacsh04a320.471/0491 aLaselva, Samuel V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMoral Foundations of Canadian Federalism :bParadoxes, Achievements, and Tragedies of Nationhood /cSamuel V. Laselva. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1996] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (281 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tTragedy, Justice, and Community as Elements of Canadian Federalism -- tFederalism as a Way of Life: The Canadian Experiment -- tConfederation and the Beginnings of Canadian Federalist Theory -- tPatriation Revisited: The Neglected Implications of Section 94 -- tDoes the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms Rest on a Mistake? -- tNation-Saving or Nation-Destroying: The Impact of the Charter of Rights on Canadian Federalism -- tReimagining Confederation: Moving Beyond the Trudeau-Lévesque Debate -- tIs Canadian Democracy Special? Mutual Recognition in a Federal System -- tA Dialogue of Democracy: Aboriginal Self-Government and Canadian Federalism -- tThe One and the Many: Pluralism, Expressivism, and the Canadian Political Nationality -- tRecovering the Moral Foundations of Canadian Federalism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLaSelva argues that Canadian federalism is founded on a vision of a nation in which multiple identities and multiple loyalties can flourish within a framework of common political nationality. He contends that this dualistic belief affects not only our understanding of Canadian identity but also a host of fundamental concepts, including fraternity, justice, democracy, and federalism itself. LaSelva offers a compelling reconsideration of Confederation and of the pivotal role of George Étienne-Cartier, one of the fathers of Confederation, in both the achievement of confederation and the creation of a distinctively Canadian federalist theory. Given the current debates about Quebec sovereignty and Native self-government, the future of the Canadian federation is uncertain. The Moral Foundations of Canadian Federalism provides a timely and novel perspective in support of Canadian federalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356600240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773566002423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773566002/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles